{"cursor":"4958","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox scientist\n| name = David Altshuler image = image_size = alt = caption = birth_date =  birth_place = Ithaca, NY death_date =  death_place = resting_place = resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = Brookline, MA citizenship = nationality = fields = workplaces =\n| Broad Institute Massachusetts General Hospital Harvard Medical School\n| alma_mater = Massachusetts Institute of Technology Harvard Medical School\n| thesis_title = thesis_url = thesis_year = doctoral_advisor = Connie Cepko\n| academic_advisors = doctoral_students = notable_students = known_for =\n| author_abbrev_bot = author_abbrev_zoo = influences = influenced = awards =\n| Curt Stern Award 2011 Outstanding Scientific\n| Achievement Award, American Diabetes Association 2012 signature =  signature_alt = website =  footnotes = spouse =\n| Jill Suttenberg Altshuler\n}}Professor 'David Matthew Altshuler' is a clinical endocrinologist and human\ngeneticist at the Broad Institute of Harvard and MIT. He is a\nProfessor of Genetics and Medicine at Harvard Medical School, and in the\nDepartment of Molecular Biology, Center for Human Genetic Research, and the\nDiabetes Unit, all at Massachusetts General Hospital. He is one of four Founding\nCore Members of the Broad Institute, and serves as the Institute's Deputy\nDirector, Chief Academic Officer, and Director of the Program in Medical and\nPopulation Genetics.\n\nAltshuler studies human genetic variation and its application to\ndisease, using information from the\nHuman Genome Project. He has co-led the SNP Consortium, International\nHapMap Project, and 1000 Genomes Project [http://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?q=david+altshuler David Altshuler\npublications in Google Scholar] His own research focuses on the genetic\nbasis of Type 2 Diabetes, and his laboratory has contributed to mapping dozens\nof gene variants that are associated with risk of Type 2 Diabetes, lipid levels,\nmyocardial infarction, rheumatoid arthritis, lupus, prostate cancer, and other\ndisorders.\n\nAltshuler received his Bachelor of Science from Massachusetts Institute of\nTechnology, his Ph.D from Harvard University, and his M.D. from\nHarvard Medical School. He completed his internship, residency, and\nclinical fellowship training at Massachusetts General Hospital.\n\nAmong his awards are election to the American Society for Clinical\nInvestigation, the Association of American Physicians, and the Institute of\nMedicine. He is a member of the Board of Directors of the American Society of\nHuman Genetics and of Vertex Pharmaceuticals. In 2011 he won the Curt Stern\nAward of the American Society of Human Genetics, and in 2012 the Outstanding\nScientific Achievement Award of the American Diabetes Association.\n","linknr":221,"url":"David_Altshuler","recorded":1376425868,"links":["/w/index.php?title=David_Altshuler&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=David_Altshuler&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Altshuler","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.visualEditor.viewPageTarget.noscript&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Broad_Institute","/